    "type": "Apartments",
    "description": "A North Amherst community that leans residential and family-oriented rather than student-social — the on-site amenity package is a clear step up from what most properties at this distance offer.\r\n\r\n🏠 The Community\r\nThe tenant base mixes families, working professionals, and grad students, which gives the property a calmer evening vibe than the undergrad-heavy complexes closer to campus. A fitness centre, a playground, and a fire pit sit on-site, along with reliable parking — the combination is closer to what you'd expect from a suburban residential community than a student-facing property. Recent turnover: the management company changed hands recently, and residents rate the new team as middling — not actively problematic, but not a standout either.\r\n\r\n💡 What's Included\r\nThree layouts are in rotation: 1 Bed / 1 Bath (686 sqft), 2 Bed / 2 Bath (851 sqft), and 3 Bed / 2 Bath (1,069 sqft). Kitchens come equipped to standard. On-site fitness centre and playground are open to residents. Heat and electricity are handled separately from rent.\r\n\r\n🚌 Getting Around\r\nAbout 1.5 mi from UMass — a 30-minute walk, or a few minutes on PVTA Route 31 or 33. Bus stops sit within the complex, which is convenient, but two transit gotchas are worth flagging: the last campus-bound bus runs around 9 pm, and Route 33's weekend schedule is thin. Grocery stores are far enough to need a car or a deliberate bus trip. Residents rate amenity access at 2/5 and commute at 4/5 on that basis.\r\n\r\n✅ Good To Know\r\nTypical per-tenant costs: claiming the living room as your space runs $585–$950 a month, while a private bedroom falls between $700 and $1,150 — a wide range depending on the unit size. Most apartments house two to four roommates. Overall satisfaction lands at 4/5; the quiet environment, fire pit, and previously-competitive rent all drive positive reviews, while the late-night transit gap and grocery distance are the consistent gripes.",
